{"id":"1906.00762","submitter":"Yael Naze","authors":"Yael Naze, Gregor Rauw, Stefan Czesla, Laurent Mahy, Fran Campos","title":"Variations on a theme -- the puzzling behaviour of Schulte 12","comments":"accepted by A&A","journal-ref":"A&A 627, A99 (2019)","doi":"10.1051/0004-6361/201935141","report-no":null,"categories":"astro-ph.SR","license":"http://arxiv.org/licenses/nonexclusive-distrib/1.0/","abstract":"  One of the first massive stars detected in X-rays, Schulte 12 has remained a\npuzzle in several aspects. In particular, its extreme brightness both in the\nvisible and X-ray ranges is intriguing. Thanks to Swift and XMM-Newton\nobservations covering ~5000d, we report the discovery of a regular 108d\nmodulation in X-ray flux of unknown origin. The minimum in the high-energy flux\nappears due to a combination of increased absorption and decreased intrinsic\nemission. We examined in parallel the data from a dedicated spectroscopic and\nphotometric monitoring in the visible and near-IR domains, complemented by\narchives. While a similar variation timescale is found in those data, they do\nnot exhibit the strict regular clock found at high energies. Changes in line\nprofiles cannot be related to binarity but rather correspond to non-radial\npulsations. Considering the substantial revision of the distance of Schulte 12\nfrom the second GAIA data release, the presence of such oscillations agrees\nwell with the evolutionary status of Schulte 12, as it lies in an instability\nregion of the HR diagram.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Mon, 3 Jun 2019 12:54:34 GMT"}],"update_date":"2020-12-09"}
